%I A395643 #22 Jun 14 2026 21:51:07
%S A395643 2,3,5,7,10,11,13,14,17,19,22,23,26,29,31,33,34,37,38,39,41,43,46,47,
%T A395643 51,53,57,58,59,61,62,67,68,69,71,73,74,76,79,82,83,86,87,89,92,93,94,
%U A395643 97,101,103,106,107,109,111,113,116,118,122,123,124
%N A395643 Numbers k whose largest prime factor exceeds k^(2/3).
%C A395643 Numbers k such that A006530(k)^3 > k^2, where A006530(k) is the largest prime factor of k.
%C A395643 Equivalently, numbers k having no divisor in the interval [k^(1/3), sqrt(k)]; that is, the central divisor A033676(k) is less than k^(1/3). (If the largest prime factor P > k^(2/3), then every divisor not exceeding sqrt(k) divides k/P < k^(1/3), so A033676(k) < k^(1/3).)
%C A395643 Every prime is a term. No term is a prime power p^e with e >= 2.
%C A395643 Subset of A064052 (numbers k with largest prime factor > sqrt(k)), the case with exponent 1/2 in place of 2/3.
%C A395643 A396205(n) is the number of terms not exceeding n.
%C A395643 The number of terms not exceeding x is asymptotic to x*log(3/2) = 0.405465...*x.
%F A395643 a(n) ~ n/log(3/2) = 2.466303...*n.
%e A395643 10 is a term: its largest prime factor is 5, and 5^3 = 125 > 100 = 10^2; equivalently, 10 has no divisor in [10^(1/3), sqrt(10)] = [2.15..., 3.16...].
%e A395643 12 is not a term: its largest prime factor is 3, and 3^3 = 27 < 144 = 12^2; equivalently, the divisor 3 lies in [12^(1/3), sqrt(12)] = [2.28..., 3.46...].
%t A395643 Select[Range[2, 200], FactorInteger[#][[-1, 1]]^3 > #^2 &]
%o A395643 (PARI) isok(k) = vecmax(factor(k)[,1])^3 > k^2;
%o A395643 select(isok, [2..200])
%Y A395643 Cf. A006530, A033676, A064052, A396205.
%K A395643 nonn,easy
%O A395643 1,1
%A A395643 _Eric Fodge_, Jun 09 2026
